<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-274-025  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 274 025.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 23 1989 v23 n3 p45(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Atlanta tests laptops and curbside clinics. (health care formobile, homeless population)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brandel, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An Atlanta, GA, social services agency is offering the firstcomputerized tracking of homeless individuals' health records inan effort to improve their medical care.andP;  The program involvesthree mobile units which deliver curb-side services.andP;  Records areupdated by the curb-side team on a microcomputer and data istransmitted via modem to a central computer site.andP;  The teams canalso call up patient information from the data base, whichcross-references social worker input.andP;  Linus Technologies'Write-Top, which permits data entry with an electronic pen ratherthan keyboard, makes the system easy to use for workers notfamiliar with computer technology.andP;  The health services group'smission is to track and treat Atlanta's 10,000 to 12,000 sick andinjured homeless, who tend to arrive with relatively seriousproblems but seldom see a single clinic regularly.andP;  The mobileunit program is not yet fully implemented and may never grow toserve all the homeless, says coordinator Bob Stokes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Medical RecordsHealth CareNetworksIssues-Society.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>